{{expand Spanish|date=February 2017}}
{{for|the Cuban song genre|Bolero}}
[[File:Bolero dance pattern.png|thumb|Bolero [[rhythm]].<ref>Blatter, Alfred 2007. ''Revisiting music theory: a guide to the practice''. p28 ISBN 0-415-97440-2.</ref>]]
The '''bolero''' is a 3/4 dance<ref>(see [[Time signature]] and [[meter (music)]])</ref> that originated in Spain in the late 18th century, a combination of the [[contradanza]] and the [[sevillana]].<ref name="Morales, p120">Morales, p120</ref> Dancer [[Sebastiano Carezo]] is credited with inventing the dance in 1780.<ref>[http://www.jstor.org/stable/830283 Journal of the American Musicological Society] '''24''', (Autumn, 1971), p. 480</ref> It is danced by either a [[solo (music)|solo]]ist or a couple. It is in a moderately slow tempo and is performed to music which is sung and accompanied by [[castanets]] and [[guitar]]s with lyrics of five to seven syllables in each of four lines per verse. It is in [[time signature|triple time]] and usually has a [[Tuplet|triplet]] on the second beat of each bar.
[[File:Lautrec marcelle lender doing the bolero in 'chilperic' 1895.jpg|thumb|right|250px|<center>Bolero dancer by [[Toulouse-Lautrec]]<br>[[Marcelle Lender]] in ''[[Chilpéric (operetta)|Chilperic]]'' - [[Hervé (composer)|Hervé]], 1895]]
==Relation to the Cuban bolero==
The [[bolero]], as a genre of [[music in Cuba]], originated in [[Santiago de Cuba]] in the last quarter of the 19th century;<ref>Cristobal Diaz offers 1885: "el bolero, creado aproximadamente para 1885". Diaz Ayala, Cristobal 1999. ''Cuando sali de la Habana 1898-1997: cien años de música cubana por el mundo''. 3rd ed, Cubanacán, San Juan P.R. p24-25</ref> it does ''not'' owe its origin to the Spanish music and song of the same name.<ref>Carpentier, Alejo 2001 [1945]. ''Music in Cuba''. Minneapolis MN.</ref>

