[[File:Ustekabe txaranga eibar.jpg|thumb|right|320px|A charanga performing in a ''pasacalles''.]]
'''Charanga''' is, in several areas of [[Spain]] a name given to represent a small [[musical band]], with [[Wind instrument|wind]] and [[percussion]] instruments, which typically plays during popular [[festivals]] (mostly in northern Spain and in the [[Valencian Community]]). The musicians are often amateurs and usually travel around as different towns celebrate their festivals.

For the most part, charangas play popular, traditional songs, which have simple rhythms and often feature risqué lyrics. Also, they often play [[medley (music)|medley]]s. The most typical type of event in which they play is the ''pasacalles'', a performance which moves along the streets of a town, while the public follows the band and dances to its tunes (and have a few beers).

In the past, the name ''charanga'' was also applied to certain military musical bands.

