Riders are seated in {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} boats for the three and a half minute ride along a water channel over {{convert|2000|ft|m|adj=on}} long.<ref name="Guidebook">Hershey's Guidebook, Western Publishing Company, 1974.</ref> Once the [[fiberglass]] boat has ascended the first lift hill, riders are only {{convert|55|ft|m}} off the ground. A second lift carries riders above the Twin Turnpike ride, preparing them for the final 35-degree, {{convert|49|ft|m|adj=on}} drop. Riders' [[photograph]]s are taken midway through the drop. The Coal Cracker shares space with several newer rides, including the [[SooperDooperLooper]] (built in 1977) and the [[Great Bear (roller coaster)|Great Bear]] (1998).
The water supply for the ride is pumped through pipes connected to a {{convert|14000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} man-made lake. This lake has the capacity to store {{convert|100000|gal|l|adj=on}} of water, and the pump system can handle approximately {{convert|25000|gal|l|adj=on}} a minute.<ref name="Guidebook"/> Guests are loaded into the boats from a revolving turntable; as the boats are always in motion this permits a higher ride capacity while providing more stability during loading and unloading.<ref>http://www.greatadventurehistory.com/Hydro%20Flume.htm</ref>
Coal Cracker ride photos are produced and sold by Get The Picture Corporation.
The Coal Cracker ride is not in operation during fall and winter events at Hersheypark, such as ''Hersheypark in the Dark'' and ''Christmas Candylane''.
Coal Cracker is also the name of a youth-led newspaper<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanlibrariesmagazine.org/2016/05/31/community-reporting/|title=Community Reporting|date=2016-05-31|website=American Libraries Magazine|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref> based in [[Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania|Mahanoy City, PA]]. It was founded in 2013 by Krista Gromalski, a Co-Founder of Heron's Eye Communications who had previously edited [[Milford Magazine]] in [[Milford, Pennsylvania|Milford, PA]] with Publisher [[Sean Strub]]. In August 2016 Coal Cracker youth-led news expanded into a [[501(c)(3) organization|501(c)(3)]] non-profit organization called Coal Cracker Kids with a mission to empower young people of Pennsylvania’s [[Anthracite|Anthracite Coal]] Region through youth-led projects that explore sense of place and promote professional development. In February 2017 Coal Cracker Kids took ownership of the former Mahanoy City Lumber & Supply Company<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://republicanherald.com/news/student-newspaper-moves-into-mahanoy-city-home-1.2228443|title=Student newspaper moves into Mahanoy City home|last=Pytak|first=By Stephen J.|access-date=2017-09-03|language=en-US}}</ref> with plans to renovate the building for use as its headquarters.
