The '''James S. Brady Press Briefing Room''' is a small theater in the [[West Wing]] of the [[White House]] where the [[White House Press Secretary]] gives briefings to the [[news media]] and the [[President of the United States]] sometimes addresses the press and the nation. It is located between the workspace assigned to the [[White House press corps]] and the office of the Press Secretary.

==History==
The first presidential press conference was held on 15 March 1913 in the Oval Office, during the presidency of [[Woodrow Wilson]]. Subsequently, through to 1969, communications from the President and general press news conferences took place in various locations, including the [[Indian Treaty Room]], the [[Harry S Truman Building|State Department auditorium]], and the White House [[East Room]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/presidential-press-conferences|title=Presidential Press Conferences|publisher=whitehousehistory.org}}</ref> 

In 1969, to accommodate the growing number of reporters assigned to the White House, President [[Richard Nixon]] had the indoor swimming pool, which had been installed by the [[March of Dimes]] for [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], covered and turned into press offices and a lounge that could double as a briefing room.<ref name=cbsn>{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Dan|title=Bush, Media Bid Press Room Farewell|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/08/02/national/main1860355.shtml|accessdate=2012-05-09|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=August 2, 2006}}</ref><ref name=life>{{cite book|last=Watson|first=Robert P.|title=Life in the White House: A Social History of the First Family and the President's House|year=2004|publisher=SUNY Press|pages=84|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FDjeFogvUy4C&pg=PA84|via=[[Google Books]]|isbn=9780791460986}}</ref>  

In 2000, the room was renamed the "James S. Brady Press Briefing Room" in honor of [[James Brady]], the press secretary who had been shot and permanently disabled during an [[Reagan assassination attempt|assassination attempt]] on President [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1981.<ref name=life/>

===Renovation===
In December 2005, the White House announced the intention to renovate the aging Press Briefing Room and cramped press corps offices.<ref name=tbclo>{{cite news|last=Vande Hei|first=Jim|title=White House Press Room To Be Closed For Makeover|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/12/26/AR2005122600591.html|accessdate=May 9, 2012|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 27, 2005}}</ref>  On August 2, 2006, the final briefing was held, and [[George W. Bush|President George W. Bush]] hosted several previous press secretaries at a closing ceremony and there was some hesitation and concern about whether the press would be allowed to return to the White House.<ref name=abcn>{{cite news|last=Yellin|first=Jessica|title=White House Press Briefing Room Redo|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=2265587&page=1#.T6s0po5c9Fg|accessdate=May 9, 2012|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=August 2, 2006}}</ref><ref name=presnyt>{{cite news|last=Stolberg|first=Sheryl Gay|title=White House Evicts Press, Temporarily. No, Really.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/03/washington/03westwing.html?ref=washington|accessdate=May 9, 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 3, 2006}}</ref> In the interim, the [[White House Conference Center]] was used as temporary location for press conferences.{{fact|date=March 2018}}

President Bush reopened the renovated room in a ribbon-cutting ceremony on the morning of July 11, 2007. He held his first formal press conference in the new briefing room the next day, following the release of a report on the progress of the Iraqi government.<ref name=reu>{{cite news|last=Spetalnick|first=Matt|title=Bush to Press: Welcome back. No questions, Please|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2007/07/11/us-bush-press-idUSN1023978320070711|accessdate=May 9, 2012|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=July 11, 2007}}</ref>  The modernization cost nearly US$8.5 million.  Of that sum, $2.5 million was funded by the media, and the remainder was funded by tax dollars.  Each correspondent's seat was priced at $1,500. Beneath the current press room lies the former White House swimming pool that has since become a computer [[server room]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The White House Staff: Inside the West Wing and Beyond |publisher=[[Brookings Institution Press]] |year=2002 |first=Bradley Hawkes |last=Patterson |isbn=9780815769514 |page=144}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=[[Worse Than Watergate: The Secret Presidency of George W. Bush]] |first=John W. |last=Dean | authorlink=John W. Dean |year=2005 |publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing |page=69 |isbn=9781740662222}}</ref>

The most noticeable change to the briefing room was a different backdrop for the press conferences, which now featured a softly lit screen flanked by mock [[column]]s, instead of the previous blue curtain.  The new [[podium]] contained video screens for [[teleconferencing]] and [[multimedia]] displays. For safety reasons, the trapdoor which provided access to the old swimming pool (a popular stop for visitors) was replaced by a discreet staircase.{{fact|date=March 2018}}

Despite complaints about the previous briefing room's lack of space, the current briefing room has only one more press seat than it did prior to renovation.{{fact|date=March 2018}}

==Seating chart==
The seating assignments are organized by the [[White House Correspondents' Association]], not by the White House press staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/press_box/2010/07/blow_up_the_white_house_briefing_room.html |title=Blow Up the White House Briefing Room|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |first=Jack |last=Shafer |date=July 21, 2010 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

