[[File:Sloppy_Joe's_Bar,_Havana_(exterior).jpg|thumb|Sloppy Joe's Bar, Havana, c.1930s.]]
[[File:Sloppy_Joe's_Bar,_Havana_(interior).jpg|thumb|Interior with [[clientele]], c.1930s.]]

'''Sloppy Joe's Bar''' is a historic [[Bar (establishment)|bar]] located in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]].  The bar reopened in 2013 after being closed for 48 years.<ref name="Reuters Sloppy Joe's">{{cite web|title=Once Havana's most famous bar, Sloppy Joe's reopens after 50 years|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/12/us-cuba-sloppyjoes-idUSBRE93B18620130412|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> 

The advent of [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]] in the United States spurred its original owner, Jose Abeal Otero, to change the emphasis from food service to liquor service<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloppy Joe's.org|url=http://www.sloppyjoes.org/}}</ref> when American tourists would visit Havana for the nightlife, the gambling and the alcohol they could not obtain back home. 

Sloppy Joe's welcomed tourists for over four decades, and offered over 80 cocktails in addition to the bar's own brand of 12-year-old [[rum]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Havana Before Castro by Peter Moruzzi, page 84}}</ref> During the 1940s and 1950s it was a magnet for American celebrities as well as tourists wanting to mingle with them.<ref name = "LP">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=z4xVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tT8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1411,2944122&dq=sloppy-joes+havana&hl=en "Cuba's Sloppy Joe's died and it will stay that way"], Reuters, cited at The Leader-Post, July 11, 1981</ref> It has been described by the [[Los Angeles Times]] as "one of the most famous bars in the world" with "almost the status of a shrine."<ref name = "LAT">[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/656595662.html?dids=656595662:656595662&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+27%2C+1981&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Sloppy+Joes+Really+Sloppy+Now--and+Empty%2C+Too&pqatl=google "Sloppy Joes Really Sloppy Now--and Empty, Too"], Los Angeles Times, August 27, 1981</ref>

The [[Cuban Revolution]] of 1959 saw the bar's business nosedive, as some 90% of Sloppy Joe's clientele was American.  A fire in the 60s closed the establishment for good.<ref name = "LAT" /> The building in which the bar was housed remained intact, resembling a ghost town with its single-piece [[mahogany]] bar and photos of celebrities.<ref name = "LP" /> The slow-paced, extensive restoration, undertaken by The Office of the Historian of Havana, began in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Havana Before Castro by Peter Moruzzi|url=http://www.havanabeforecastro.com/}}</ref>  It is located on the corner of Calle Animas and Zulueta in Havana Vieja ([[Old Havana]]). The building is located behind (on the same block as) the Plaza Hotel.

The bar, in its heyday, can be seen in the movie ''[[Our Man in Havana (film)|Our Man in Havana]]'' starring Alec Guinness<ref name = "LP" /> as it is the bar in which the character (Jim Wormold) is attempted to be recruited into the secret service.  It supposedly inspired the deli sandwich sold in northern New Jersey for over half a century by the same name, [[Sloppy joe (New Jersey)|sloppy joe]].

Renovation work on Sloppy Joe's was completed in early 2013, and its doors opened to the public on April 12th of that year.<ref name="Reuters Sloppy Joe's"/> The facade closely resembles the images from the 1950s, even down to the sign on the corner, above the arches.<ref>{{cite web|title=mercurynews.com|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/travel/ci_22484070/round-2-sloppy-joes-bar-havana-original}}</ref>

